Swap — the virtual memory pressure valve.

Swap is disk space that the kernel uses as overflow when RAM fills up. The idea is simple: pages of memory that haven't been touched in a while can be written out to swap on disk, which frees up RAM for the processes that are actively working. Later, when one of those swapped-out pages is needed again, the kernel reads it back in. Swap can be either a dedicated partition or just a regular file. The swap file is more flexible, because you can resize it without repartitioning, and it's the default on many modern distributions.

Let's create a swap file, since that's the common case. First, sudo fallocate dash-l two-G slash-swapfile creates a two-gigabyte file. Then, and this is mandatory, sudo chmod six-hundred on it, because a swap file must be readable only by root; if it's world-readable, anyone could read memory contents out of it. Then sudo mkswap formats the file as swap, and sudo swapon enables it immediately. To check what swap is active, run swapon dash-dash-show, or free dash-h, which shows both memory and swap totals. To turn it off, swapoff. And to make it persistent across reboots, add a line to fstab: slash-swapfile, none, swap, sw, zero, zero.

There's also a tuning knob called swappiness, the sysctl vm-dot-swappiness. It controls how aggressively the kernel reaches for swap. The range is zero to two hundred, and the default is sixty. Lower values tell the kernel to favour keeping things in RAM and swap less; higher values tell it to swap more readily. You set it temporarily with sudo sysctl vm-dot-swappiness equals ten, and make it permanent by putting that line in etc-sysctl-dot-conf. As rough guidance: sixty is the balanced desktop default; ten to twenty is common on servers, to favour RAM; and zero is almost never what you want.

One modern note. On machines with lots of RAM, swap matters less than it once did. But you usually still want some. Hibernation needs swap at least as big as your RAM, and even a small swap acts as a pressure-release valve when memory gets tight. Cloud VMs frequently ship with no swap at all, so adding a swap file is one of the most common first tweaks people make.
